Visit the <A HREF="../Reference/Cultivation/index.tpl">Cultivation</A> section. Kyle Kushman and Max Yields have answered this question many times.<P> 

9. <B>What about narcs/How can you tell if someone is a narc/What are the laws of entrapment?</B><BR>
There is no surefire way to tell if someone is a narc or not. Narcs are professional liars and are out to bust any drug user (often high profile/celebrity drug users), any way they can, and will use the most devious methods imaginable to do so. Most often people are not set up by a narcotics officer, they are turned in by a paid informant who is trying to avoid their own jail sentence for drug trafficking or who is getting paid a lot of money for turning in small-time drug users and dealers.<P>

It is not beyond imagination that an informer could weasel their way into an activist group, or would hang out at an activist event in order to entrap people. Beware any strangers, and do not do business with anyone you don't already know.<P>

Most often, growers or dealers are not entrapped by a narc--they are informed on by a suspicious neighbor, jealous spouse, angry "friend," or misguided acquaintance. This is the most difficult and stressful part of getting involved in any illegal activity--keeping a lid of secrecy about all aspects of the operation.<P>

If you are serious about changing the laws against marijuana, we suggest staying drug-free. If this lifestyle decision is against your principles, study these laws very carefully, take no chances for which you are not prepared to suffer consequences for, and be as discreet as possible.<P>

The simplest way to avoid being set up is to avoid doing anything with anyone you don't know.<P>

10. <B>I heard a rumor that HIGH TIMES is owned by the government/operated by the DEA/that the subscription list run by the FBI!</B><BR>
This rumor is often spread by the government and police agencies in an effort to thwart marijuana legalization efforts. For instance, the DEA heavily publicized the fact that a "HIGH TIMES subscriber" is number one on their "pot grower profile" despite the fact that they have no way of knowing if someone subscribes or not. Then again, if someone really stupid is smuggling pot wirth them from their weekend in Negril, Jamaica, they're probably the one wearing the tie-dye pot t-shirt and reading a copy of HIGH TIMES in the Customs line.<P>

Yes, if someone does decide to break the law and grow, sell or smoke marijuana, they would be insane to wear a "HIGH TIMES" t-shirt or other marijuana- or psychedelic- related clothing in public to advertise the fact. That's just common sense.<P>

Here is some more common sense: If HIGH TIMES were strictly set up as a sting operation to get subscriber's names, why don't we offer a "Bill Me Later" option? That way, we could get ten times as many names. And why don't we lower the subscription price? That way we could entrap more people. Finally, why are there 15,000 people who have subscribed to HIGH TIMES for years and years who have never received a visit from the police?<P>

As you can see, the people who believe and spread these rumors fall into two categories: morons and cops.<P>

Also, people who believe those rumors sometime think: "It must be illegal for HIGH TIMES to publish. Therefore they must have a deal with the government to turn over people who subscribe to stay in business."<P>

Yes, HIGH TIMES is illegal--in countries that do not have strong Constitutional rights like the United States of America. But in this country, HIGH TIMES is protected by the highest law in the land--The First Amendment of the Bill of Rights in our Constitution which declares: "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of grievances."<P>

Oddly enough, even after the U.S. government has investigated HIGH TIMES, harassed the magazine, and tried to pass legislation specifically designed to put us out of business, there are still people who still listen to and believe rumors that we cooperate with those bastards. And often, these rumors get pumped up whenever HIGH TIMES or the marijuana movement has enjoyed some success. Needless to say, the rumor-mongers are the same people who are NOT card-carrying members of NORML, support marijuana activist groups, or otherwise work to change the laws. Sometimes, they are even paid informants who are setting up marijuana busts.<P>

Even NORML and other legalization groups have to live with these idiotic rumors. If you want to stop the government from keep marijuana/cannabis/hemp illegal, stop spreading stupid, false rumors against HIGH TIMES and NORML. There enough rumors that are true.<P>

11. <B>HIGH TIMES has published recipes for "crank." Could you send me a copy?</B><BR>
Don't be ridiculous. HIGH TIMES magazine has never published instructions for speed, methedrine or crank. And we certainly wouldn't recommend that anyone use garbage drugs like that, much less manufacture some for distribution.<P>

12. <B>What about legal herbs/legal highs/legal ecstasy?</B><BR>
There are many herbal mixtures and preparations on the market that claim to produce certain effects. Some people enjoy them, some people don't, others get no effect at all from these things. It's impossible for HIGH TIMES to guess what kind of effect they'll have on you.<P>

Should you decide to experiment with any substances, natural or chemical, we suggest that you do so under a physician's care, or at the very least, check the dosage level very carefully and do not exceed it. Mixing alcohol or other drugs with any over the counter drugs or herbal preparations can also be very dangerous.<P>

One rule of thumb we tell advertisers and readers is that the longer an advertisement runs, the more likely that an advertiser is selling merchandise or services that are worth investing in. HIGH TIMES' longest-running advertisers--some of whom have been advertising with us for 20 years or more--are clearly the mark of a company with a large and devoted customer base.<P>

13. <B>What about the legal marijuana or herbal smoking blends that the companies sell? Is it any good?</B><BR>
Again, it's up to individual taste. The only way to find out for yourself is to try it.<P>

